quest_title:
The reaction

\( 2Cu^{+} \to Cu + Cu^{2+} \) is:
explanation_txt:
The reaction in which same chemical species undergoes both oxidation and reduction is called disproportionation reaction. In the given reaction, one \( Cu^{+} \) ion is reduced to \(Cu\) while other is oxidized to \( Cu^{2+} \).

It is due to this disproportionating property of Cuprous ion, Cuprous oxide on reaction with hot dilute sulphuric acid gives inert copper along with sulphate of copper and water.

\( \overset{+1}Cu_2O + H_2SO_4 \to \overset{0}Cu + \overset{+2}CuSO_4 + H_2O \)

quest_title: A particle moves in \(xy\) plane under the action of force \(F\) such that the value of its linear momentum \(\vec{P}\) at any instant \(t\) is \(P_{x}=2 \cot t, P_{y}=2 \sin t\), then angle between \(\vec{F}\) and \(\vec{P}\) is
explanation_txt:
\(\vec{P}=P_{x}+P_{y}=2 \cot t \hat{i}+2 \sin t \hat{j}\)
\(\vec{F}=\cfrac{d \vec{P}}{d t}=-2 \sin t \hat{i}+2 \cos t \hat{j}\)

Now,

\(\vec{P} \cdot \vec{F}=(2 \cos t \hat{i}+2 \sin t \hat{j}) \cdot(-2 \sin t \hat{i}+2 \cos t \hat{j})\)
\(\vec{P} \cdot \vec{F}=-4 \sin t \cos t+4 \sin t \cos t\)
\(\vec{P} \cdot \vec{F}=0\)

Since dot product of two vector is 0 so angle is 90°.

quest_title: By exerting a certain amount of pressure on an ice block, you
ans3_txt: Make it melt at a faster rate
explanation_txt:
Here's the reason explained by Brent Nelson, PhD student of UC Berkley:

The phenomenon of lowering of melting point of ice on exerting pressure can be explained in terms of LeChatelier's principle. This principle states that when a system is in equilibrium, any external changes that try to take it out of equilibrium (like applying pressure to ice) will cause the system to adjust in a way to counteract that change. In this case, if you increase the pressure on the ice the ice-water system wants to try to lower it again. It can do that by making itself fit into a smaller volume. But since water fills a smaller volume when it's liquid, rather than solid, it will go to a lower melting point -- allowing more solid to become liquid.
